ork and care for older parents, disabled children and partners: convergent or separate paths in three welfare systems? -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs populations age around the world, increasing efforts are required from both families and governments to secure care and support for older and disabled people.At the same time both women and men are expected to increase and lengthen their participation in paid work, which makes combining caring and working a burning issue for social and employment policy and economic sustainability. International discussion about the reconciliation of work and care has previously focused mostly on childcare. Combining paid work and family care widens the debate, bringing into discussion the experiences of those providing support to their partners, older relatives and disabled or seriously ill children. The book analyses the situations of these working carers in Nordic, liberal and East Asian welfare systems. Highlighting what can be learned from individual experiences, the book analyses the changing welfare and labour market policies which shape the lives of working carers in Finland, Sweden, Australia, England, Japan and Taiwan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCaregiversvCross-cultural studies. 0aChildren with disabilitiesxCare. 0aFamily policyvCross-cultural studies. 0aOlder peoplexCare. 0aSickxCare. 0aWork and familyvCross-cultural studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aCass, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChang, Heng-Hao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChou, Yueh-Ching, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngwall, Kristina, econtri